Years ago, I found this DIY hack in Popular Science to boost wi-fi reception.

Take a cell phone - doesn't matter the age - and wrap LAN cable in a coil around the phone, plugging one end into your computer.

Turn the phone on.

No matter if you've registered the phone or not, it still has a radio receiver, and the coils around it reinforce the incoming signals and pump them into your computer's LAN port, resulting in better reception and fewer dropped frames. I can attest to the fact that it really works, adding at least 2 bars to signal strength from various sources. Might be worth a shot to see if this idea can be adapted to work with the boroscope's wi-fi transceiver.
